  "text": "<html>\r\n    <head>\r\n    <style>\r\n        .unselectable {\r\n          -webkit-user-select: none;\r\n          -webkit-touch-callout: none;\r\n          -moz-user-select: none;\r\n          -ms-user-select: none;\r\n          user-select: none;\r\n        }\r\n      <\/style>\r\n      <\/head>\r\n\r\n<body class=\"unselectable\">\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">LEGITIMACY&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Legitimacy is the recognition and acceptance by the citizens that a government is legally instituted. In other words, it is the conformity of government and its act with the law. A legitimate government is a government with the backing of the people and law of the land.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Legitimacy ensures stability in government.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Type of legitimacy<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Traditional legitimacy: This arises from custom and tradition and is found in monarchy or tribe where people support their leaders because they inherited position by customs.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Charismatic legitimacy: This arises when people give support to leaders because they possess charm or personality that dominate them and make them obey their commands.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Legal-rational: This is institutional and based on law. It arises when institutions or leaders form laws that the people feel are beneficial to them and as such give them supports.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Sovereignty&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Sovereignty is the supreme power of a state to make laws and enforce them. It is the ultimate power of state. It can also be defined as a state of political independence. Sovereignty is associated with Jean Rousseau, John Locke, Thomas Hobbes, Grotius, and Jeah Bodin. Jean Bodin is the father of sovereignty. The concept of sovereignty was first used by Bodin in 1576 in his book entitled Six Books Concerning the State.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Characteristics of Sovereignty<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Absoluteness, comprehensiveness, permanence, indivisibility, exclusiveness and independence.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Nation-state is synonymous with ----<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. self-actualization, B. sovereignty, C. liberation, D. nationalism<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. sovereignty<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">One major weakness of the Independence Constitution is that it&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. failed to provide the country with full sovereignty. B. gave total independence to Nigeria, C. gave full powers to the Supreme Court in Nigeria, D. empowered Britain to continue to rule.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. failed to provide the country with full sovereignty.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In a democratic government, political sovereignty is vested in the<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. legislature, B. elite, C. executive, D. electorate<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D In a democratic government,<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">political<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">authority is<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">vested<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">in the people. it is a form of<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">government<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">in which the people, or some significant portion of them, retain<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">sovereignty<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">over the<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">government<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">and where offices of state are not granted through heritage.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Authority&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Authority refers to rights to make binding decisions and secure obedience. Authority is a legalized power; that is, power backed by law. It is the right to direct and command people. A German sociologist, Marx Weber, who was first to develop the ideas of authority, identified three types:&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Legal rational authority, which is based on law or constitution of the land and is exerted by government officials.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Traditional authority, which is anchored on traditional norms and customs, e.g. patriarchy, gerontocracy and charismatic\/personality authority, which is based on special natural qualities or personality of a leader.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Religious or sacred authority is exercised by religious leaders over their followers while political authority is possessed by elected and appointed political office holders. Authority is exerted based on influence, persuasion and acceptance. Authority is a legitimized power and does not rely on the use of force or threat of sanction td secure compliance. The symbols of authority include national flag, coat of arms, mace etc.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Difference between power and authority<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">1. Power is ability to influence the conduct of others but authority is the right.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">2. Resistance to power is lawful but resistance to authority is unlawful<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">3. Power involves mainly coercion, threat and sanction but authority IS based on acceptance and recognition of the right to give command<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">4. Power may secure obedience but not allegiance but authority secures allegiance&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">5. Power may be legal or illegal but authority is legal&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Personal authority is synonymous with&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. Charismatic authority, B. instruments; authority&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. sacred authority, D. Legal authority<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. Charismatic authority.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Which of the following is a legal source of political authority?&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">a. Power from the gun, b. Economic power, c. Minority power, d. Power from the electorate.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. Power from the electorate.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The ability to command obedience is called&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">a. authority, b. influence, c. legitimacy, d. mobilisation.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. Authority&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n \r\n<\/body>\r\n\r\n<\/html>",
  "chapIndex": "LEGITIMACY"
}